                            <comment id="17954196" author="JIRAUSER309836" created="Tue, 27 May 2025 02:08:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi, I&#8217;d like to work on this issue. I&#8217;ve verified the bug and can reproduce it locally.&lt;br/&gt;
I&#8217;m preparing a fix for the malformed input handling in &lt;tt&gt;getShortCanonicalName()&lt;/tt&gt; and will include a test case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#8211; Purnabhishek Sripathi&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18011340" author="JIRAUSER309763" created="Fri, 1 Aug 2025 03:46:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;You&apos;re right to raise concerns about the behavior of &lt;tt&gt;ClassUtils.getShortCanonicalName&lt;/tt&gt;, but I believe the test input used in this case &#8212; &lt;tt&gt;&quot;[String&quot;&lt;/tt&gt; &#8212; is not a valid canonical or internal JVM class name.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the JVM, the internal name for a one-dimensional array of &lt;tt&gt;String&lt;/tt&gt; is &lt;tt&gt;&quot;[Ljava.lang.String;&quot;&lt;/tt&gt;. The input &lt;tt&gt;&quot;[String&quot;&lt;/tt&gt; is malformed and doesn&apos;t conform to any expected format (neither canonical nor internal JVM type descriptors).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While &lt;tt&gt;[String&lt;/tt&gt; is invalid, the method should not silently return &lt;tt&gt;short[]&lt;/tt&gt;. Instead it should validate input and either throw an exception or fail-safe return, to avoid misleading outputs.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18017574" author="JIRAUSER310828" created="Tue, 2 Sep 2025 02:34:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been fixed in the Git master branch and the latest snapshot builds.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/commons-lang/pull/1437&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;PR for reference&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please verify your use cases.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For malformed input, an &lt;tt&gt;IllegalArgumentException&lt;/tt&gt; is now thrown with a descriptive message.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
